du, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Barton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of numerous places called with Old English <i>bere</i> or <i>bær</i> ‘barley’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘enclosure, settlement’, i.e. an outlying grange. Compare   Barwick  . The name is also found in Ireland, where it has been Gaelicized as <b>de Bartún</b>.","Polish (<b>Bartoń</b>); Czech and Slovak (mainly <b>Bartoň</b>): from a pet form of the personal name Polish <i>Bartłomiej</i>, Czech <i>Bartoloměj</i>, Slovak <i>Bartolomej</i>, from Latin <i>Bartholomaeus</i> (see   Bartholomew  ). This surname is also found in Germany."],"variants":[{"name":"Barwick","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of various places called Berwick or Barwick, for example in Northumberland, Norfolk, Somerset, and Yorkshire, from Old English <i>bere</i> ‘barley’ + <i>wīc</i> ‘outlying farm building’, i.e. a granary lying some distance away from the main settlement.","North German: habitational name from a place called Berwick, near Soest, in Westphalia."]}]},{"name":"Leysing","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: variant of   Lessig   1.","Germanized form of Sorbian <b>Lěsnik</b> (and possibly also of some other similar or like-sounding Slavic surname): topographic name for a forest dweller or an occupational name for a forester, <i>lěsnik</i>, derived from <i>lěs</i> ‘wood, forest’. Compare   Lesnik   1 and   Lessig   2."],"variants":[{"name":"Lessig","meanings":["Germanized form of Sorbian <b>Lěsik</b>, a variant of <b>Lěsk</b> (see   Lieske   2), and perhaps also of <b>Lěsnik</b> (see   Lessing   2) or some other derivative of <i>lěs</i> ‘wood, forest’.","German: nickname from the dialect bird name <i>Lessig</i>, borrowed from Old Slavic <i>dleskь</i>, a word denoting any bird of genus Coccothraustes, especially ‘hawfinch’."]},{"name":"Lesnik","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Polish Alojzy, Piotr.","Polish (<b>Leśnik</b>) and Slovak (<b>Lesník</b>): occupational name for a forester, Polish <i>leśnik</i>, Slovak <i>lesník</i>, derived from Polish dialect and Slovak <i>les</i> ‘wood, forest’. The homonymous Sorbian cognate, <b>Lěsnik</b>, is apparently found in Germanized forms, only (see   Lessing  ).","Slovenian: topographic name for a forest dweller, derived from dialect <i>les</i> ‘forest’."]},{"name":"Lessin","meanings":["German: possibly a variant of   Lessing  ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Leysing de Barton II was born in 1120, in Barton, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom as the son of Leysing de Barton. He married Agatha of Barton about 1149, in Barton, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. He died about 1170, in Somme, Picardie, France, at the age of 51."},"et":{"1120–Abt 1170":"1120–umbes 1170","1115–Male":"1115–Surnud","1120–1170":"1120–1170","–Male":"Surnud","1125–1212":"1125–1212","1150–1195":"1150–1195","1160–Female":"1160–Surnud","1090–1150":"1090–1150","Abt 1130":"umbes 1130","1090":"1090","1115":"1115","1125":"1125","1212":"1212","about 1149":"umbes 1149","1120":"1120","1195":"1195","1150":"1150","1160":"1160","Abt 1170":"umbes 1170","1170":"1170","Barton, Gloucestershire, England":"Barton, Gloucestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Barton, Preston, Lancashire, England":"Barton, Lancashire, England","Somme, Picardy, France":"Somme, Picardie, Prantsusmaa","Barton, Lancashire, 